Section Summary: In 1820, the remains of a great ancient Egyptian city were discovered in Middle Egypt, and in 1888, a number of clay tablets with writing were found near the ruins of Tell el Amarna. The tablets, which dated back to around 1400 B.C., were part of the Egyptian state archives and consisted mainly of letters from Egyptian officials and foreign kings to the Egyptian monarch. The letters were written in Babylonian cuneiform, indicating that this language was used for diplomacy in the East at that time. The discovery of the tablets provided valuable insights into the administration and court of the Egyptian pharaohs, particularly Amenophis III and IV, who ruled during a period of relative peace and focused on artistic and cultural pursuits. The tablets also revealed the complex system of writing and communication used by the ancient Egyptians and their foreign counterparts.
