Section section_02 (Chars 8547–12782):
Section Summary: The life of King Amenophis IV, also known as Akhenaten, is not well understood, but it is believed that he intended to reform the Egyptian religion and reduce the power of the priests of Amon in Thebes. He introduced a new doctrine, known as "the doctrine," which emphasized the worship of the Sun's Disk, or Aten, and led to a break with the old religion. The king and his officials adopted new names and titles, and a new capital city, Akhet-Aten, was built to replace Thebes. The new doctrine was not widely accepted, and many officials and vassals in Syria and Palestine continued to refer to the old god Amon, with only a few acknowledging the change. The introduction of the Aten dogma represented a significant shift in Egyptian religion, with a greater emphasis on natural phenomena and a more spontaneous expression of devout feeling.
